<p>Now, when we run <code>mvn javafx:run</code>, the program will be
started.</p>
</content></item><item><title>Minecraft Modding on 1.8.9: Setting up Java</title><link>https://vibe-876.github.io/posts/setting-up-java.html</link><description>>:3</description><content type="html"><h1 id="getting-started">Getting Started</h1>
<p>So you want to program a Minecraft mod for 1.8.9. It's a niche genre
of person who wants to do that, I can respect it. If you only came here
for source code examples, they can be found on my Github here (fix me
before posting).</p>
<p>The first thing you're going to need is a JDK, or Java Development
Toolkit, and for 1.8.9, you'll need Java 8 specifically. I personally
use OpenJDK, which can be downloaded <a
href="https://github.com/adoptium/temurin8-binaries/releases/tag/jdk8u482-b08">here</a>,
and you'll want the version starting with
<code>OpenJDK8U-jdk_&lt;your-cpu-arch&gt;_&lt;your-OS&gt;</code>. For
example, if you're on windows, with a 64 bit x64 CPU, then you download
<code>OpenJDK8U-jdk_x64_windows_hotspot_8u482b08.msi</code> (if you
don't know which is you, it's probably this one). After getting that,
you'll also need the 1.8.9 <a
href="https://files.minecraftforge.net/net/minecraftforge/forge/index_1.8.9.html">MDK</a>
(Minecraft Development Toolkit), <a
href="https://git-scm.com/install//windows">git</a>, and <a
href="https://eclipseide.org/">Eclipse IDE</a> (you can use whatever IDE
you want, but this guide will be in Eclipse, because they gave me a pen
at FOSDEM). And if you don't already have a Github account, now would
probably be the time to make one (much like the editor, it doesn't have
to be Github, but I'll be focusing on it).</p>
<p>After going through the Java installer, go into powershell, and go to
wherever you downloaded the MDK zip to. You can either do this by
opening the folder in File Explorer, right clicking, and clicking open
in terminal, or by using the <code>cd</code> command, which would look
something like this (<code>cd</code> stands for "change directory";
directory is just another name for folder).</p>
<pre class="shell"><code>cd &#39;\.Downloads\&#39;
</code></pre>
<p>Then, create a new directory called
<code>minecraft-forge-1.8.9</code>, move the MDK zip file into it, and
then unzip it. Again, you can do this with the File Explorer, or with a
command.</p>
<pre class="shell"><code>unzip forge-1.8.9-11.15.1.2318-1.8.9-mdk.zip
</code></pre>
<p>Now, simply run <code>.\gradlew.bat runClient</code>, and modded
Minecraft will start (note that it might take a while trying to download
things). Granted, there are barely any running in it, but we'll fix that
soon enough.</p>
<h1 id="whats-that-gradlew.bat-thing">What's That Gradlew.bat
thing?</h1>
<p><code>gradlew.bat</code> is a little program that controls something
called <a href="https://gradle.org/">Gradle</a>. Gradle is a build
system, which is a piece of software that helps us compile and run code.
Some projects have thousands of files, and it would be a pain to compile
each of those by hand, so these programs do it for us.</p>
<h1 id="setting-up-eclipse">Setting up Eclipse</h1>
